# TypeScript design philosophy

TypeScript's type system is the design tool. Use it to make wrong code
impossible to write — and when you can't, to make it loud at compile
time.

Companion reading: *Effective TypeScript* (Dan Vanderkam),
*Total TypeScript* (Matt Pocock).

## Type-first thinking

Sketch the *types* before the implementation. The signatures and the
data shapes are the design.

```ts
// First: what does the function take? What does it return?
function placeOrder(
  cmd: PlaceOrderCommand,
  repo: OrderRepository,
): Promise<Result<OrderId, OrderError>>;

// Now the implementation has nowhere to hide.
```

If the type is hard to write, the operation is hard to specify — fix
the spec, not the code.

## Make invalid states unrepresentable

The single most useful TS pattern.

### Discriminated unions over "the bag of optionals"

```ts
// Bad: every field is optional; many illegal combinations
type Order = {
  status: string;
  paidAt?: Date;
  shippedAt?: Date;
  refundReason?: string;
};

// Good: each variant carries only the fields that can exist in it
type Order =
  | { status: "placed"; placedAt: Date }
  | { status: "paid"; placedAt: Date; paidAt: Date }
  | { status: "shipped"; placedAt: Date; paidAt: Date; shippedAt: Date }
  | { status: "refunded"; placedAt: Date; refundReason: string };
```

A `switch (order.status)` now narrows the type and TypeScript checks
exhaustiveness if you ask it to (see `patterns.md`).

### Branded types for domain primitives

```ts
type Brand<T, B> = T & { readonly __brand: B };
type UserId  = Brand<string, "UserId">;
type OrderId = Brand<string, "OrderId">;

function userId(s: string): UserId { return s as UserId; }
function orderId(s: string): OrderId { return s as OrderId; }

function charge(user: UserId, order: OrderId) { /* … */ }

charge(orderId("o1"), userId("u1")); // ❌ compile error: arguments swapped
```

Zero runtime cost. Eliminates a class of argument-swap bugs.

### `as const` for literal-typed configuration

```ts
const STATUSES = ["placed", "paid", "shipped", "refunded"] as const;
type Status = typeof STATUSES[number];   // "placed" | "paid" | ...
```

The runtime array and the compile-time union stay in sync.

## Read-only by default

`readonly` and `ReadonlyArray<T>` should be the default; mutability is
opt-in.

- Function parameters: `readonly T[]` unless you actually need to push.
- Returned arrays: same.
- Class fields that don't change after construction: `readonly`.
- Constants: `as const`.

```ts
function summarise(orders: readonly Order[]): Summary { /* … */ }
```

A `readonly T[]` accepts a regular `T[]`, so callers aren't burdened.

## Composition over inheritance

Same heuristic as the rest of the codebase. Reach for:

- **Interface / type composition** for "has-a":

  ```ts
  type WithTimestamps = { createdAt: Date; updatedAt: Date };
  type Order = WithTimestamps & { id: OrderId; total: Money };
  ```

- **Function composition** for behavior pipelines.

- **Dependency injection** via constructor / parameter rather than
  inheriting from a base class:

  ```ts
  class PlaceOrderUseCase {
    constructor(
      private readonly orders: OrderRepository,
      private readonly clock: Clock,
    ) {}
    async execute(cmd: PlaceOrderCommand): Promise<OrderId> { /* … */ }
  }
  ```

Reserve `class extends class` for framework conventions that require
it (e.g. `extends Error`, `extends React.Component` if you still use
class components).

## `unknown` over `any`

When you can't (or shouldn't) name a type yet, `unknown`. The compiler
will force you to narrow before use — which is the entire point.

```ts
function parseJson(text: string): unknown { return JSON.parse(text); }

const data = parseJson(text);
if (isOrderDTO(data)) {  // user-defined type predicate
  // data is OrderDTO here
}
```

For untrusted input from the network or disk, use a **schema
validator** (`zod`, `valibot`, `arktype`). Validate once at the
boundary; the inferred type flows through the rest of the system.

```ts
const OrderDTO = z.object({ id: z.string().uuid(), total: z.number().positive() });
type OrderDTO = z.infer<typeof OrderDTO>;
```

## Exhaustive checking

When matching on a discriminated union, add an `assertNever` arm so
adding a new variant is a compile error at every switch:

```ts
function describe(o: Order): string {
  switch (o.status) {
    case "placed":   return "placed";
    case "paid":     return "paid";
    case "shipped":  return "shipped";
    case "refunded": return "refunded";
    default: {
      const _exhaustive: never = o;
      throw new Error(`Unhandled status: ${JSON.stringify(_exhaustive)}`);
    }
  }
}
```

The `: never` annotation fails at the new variant; the runtime throw
covers cases narrowing miss (shouldn't happen, but defence-in-depth).

## The Clean Architecture mapping

Same as the rest of the project:

| Layer | TS expression |
| --- | --- |
| `domain` | Plain types, pure functions, class methods. **No `fetch`, no DB driver, no framework imports.** Define `interface OrderRepository` here. |
| `application` | Use-case classes/functions that take `OrderRepository` etc. via DI. |
| `infrastructure` | Concrete implementations: `PrismaOrderRepository`, `FetchHttpClient`. |
| `presentation` | HTTP framework (Express/Fastify/Next) routes that parse → call use case → render. The composition root lives here. |

## Async hygiene

- Don't fire-and-forget promises in production paths. The lint catches
  them; keep `no-floating-promises` on.
- Concurrency: `Promise.all` for "all must succeed",
  `Promise.allSettled` for "tell me what happened to each".
- Cancellation: pass an `AbortSignal` through long-running operations.
  Most modern fetch/IO APIs accept one.
- Avoid mixing callbacks and promises. Wrap callback APIs in
  `util.promisify` (Node) or a small adapter.

## Performance hygiene (not premature)

- Iterators / generators / streams when data is large. Don't materialise
  a million-row result into an array.
- Avoid creating new arrays inside hot loops; use `for` for the hottest
  paths.
- Don't `JSON.stringify` for object equality. Use `lodash.isEqual` or
  a structural equality helper.
- Use typed arrays (`Uint8Array`, etc.) for binary data.
